  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some useful websites for students?",
  "response": "There are a multitude of websites that can be highly beneficial for students across various aspects of their academic and personal lives. Here is a list of some of the most useful websites:\n\n1. **Khan Academy (khanacademy.org)**\n   - Khan Academy offers free online courses, lessons, and practice exercises in various subjects including math, science, programming, history, and more. It's particularly useful for self-paced learning and supplementing classroom education.\n\n2. **Coursera (coursera.org)**\n   - Coursera partners with universities and organizations worldwide to offer a wide range of courses. Students can learn new skills or delve deeper into subjects of interest through these online classes, many of which offer certificates upon completion.\n\n3. **Google Scholar (scholar.google.com)**\n   - Google Scholar is an excellent resource for research. It allows students to search for scholarly literature across many disciplines and sources, including articles, theses, books, and conference papers.\n\n4. **Grammarly (grammarly.com)**\n   - Grammarly is a tool that helps students with writing by checking for grammar, spelling, and punctuation errors. It can be particularly useful for non-native English speakers or anyone looking to improve their writing.\n\n5. **Quizlet (quizlet.com)**\n   - Quizlet is a study tool that allows students to create digital flashcards, practice tests, and study games. It\u2019s an effective way to memorize and review material for exams.\n\n6. **Evernote (evernote.com)**\n   - Evernote is a note-taking app that helps students keep their notes organized. It syncs across devices, making it easy to access notes from anywhere.\n\n7. **Chegg (chegg.com)**\n   - Chegg offers textbook rentals, homework help, online tutoring, and scholarship opportunities. It\u2019s a one-stop shop for many academic needs.\n\n8. **TED-Ed (ed.ted.com)**\n   - TED-Ed offers engaging animated video lessons on a wide range of topics. These can be great for stimulating interest in a subject or as a break from traditional studying methods.\n\n9. **MIT OpenCourseWare (ocw.mit.edu)**\n   - MIT OpenCourseWare provides free access to almost all MIT course content. It\u2019s an excellent resource for students interested in advanced or specialized subjects.\n\n10. **Duolingo (duolingo.com)**\n    - For students interested in learning a new language, Duolingo offers a fun and effective way to do so for free.\n\n11. **Zotero (zotero.org)**\n    - Zotero is a free, easy-to-use tool to help you collect, organize, cite, and share research sources. It's particularly useful for managing references and creating citations.\n\n12. **Canva (canva.com)**\n    - Canva is a user-friendly graphic design tool that students can use to create presentations, posters, and other visual projects.\n\nEach of these websites serves a different purpose and can be incredibly beneficial depending on a student's specific needs, from studying and research to organization and creative projects.",
